 255:     """
 256:     SeedSequence(entropy=None, *, spawn_key=(), pool_size=4)
 257: 
 258:     SeedSequence mixes sources of entropy in a reproducible way to set the
 259:     initial state for independent and very probably non-overlapping
 260:     BitGenerators.
 261: 
 262:     Once the SeedSequence is instantiated, you can call the `generate_state`
 263:     method to get an appropriately sized seed. Calling `spawn(n) <spawn>` will
 264:     create ``n`` SeedSequences that can be used to seed independent
 265:     BitGenerators, i.e. for different threads.
 266: 
 267:     Parameters
 268:     ----------
 269:     entropy : {None, int, sequence[int]}, optional
 270:         The entropy for creating a `SeedSequence`.
 271:     spawn_key : {(), sequence[int]}, optional
 272:         A third source of entropy, used internally when calling
 273:         `SeedSequence.spawn`
 274:     pool_size : {int}, optional
 275:         Size of the pooled entropy to store. Default is 4 to give a 128-bit
 276:         entropy pool. 8 (for 256 bits) is another reasonable choice if working
 277:         with larger PRNGs, but there is very little to be gained by selecting
 278:         another value.
 279:     n_children_spawned : {int}, optional
 280:         The number of children already spawned. Only pass this if
 281:         reconstructing a `SeedSequence` from a serialized form.
 282: 
 283:     Notes
 284:     -----
 285: 
 286:     Best practice for achieving reproducible bit streams is to use
 287:     the default ``None`` for the initial entropy, and then use
 288:     `SeedSequence.entropy` to log/pickle the `entropy` for reproducibility:
 289: 
 290:     >>> sq1 = np.random.SeedSequence()
 291:     >>> sq1.entropy
 292:     243799254704924441050048792905230269161  # random
 293:     >>> sq2 = np.random.SeedSequence(sq1.entropy)
 294:     >>> np.all(sq1.generate_state(10) == sq2.generate_state(10))
